\prob{2}

\subprob{a}

Observe that $(y/x)^2 - x = y^2/x^2 - x = x^3/x^2 - x = 0$ in the
fraction field of $A$, so $y/x$ is integral over $A$. On the other
hand, suppose we had $f \in k[x,y]$ such that $f^2 - x \in (y^2 -
x^3)$. Clearly $f$ can have no constant term, but then $f^2$ can have
no linear term, a contradiction. Thus $y/x \notin A$.

\subprob{b}

Let $\phi : \A^1 \to X$ the map $t \mapsto (t^3, t^2)$. Since $\phi$
is a polynomial map, $\phi$ is regular, and in particular
continuous. We have an inverse map sending $(x,y) \mapsto x/y$ when $y
\ne 0$ and $(0,0) \mapsto 0$, so $\phi$ is a bijection. Since closed
sets in $\A^1$ are finite unions of points (or the whole space), to
show $\phi^{-1}$ is continuous it suffices to show $\phi^{-1}(t)$ is
closed for $t \in \A^1$. But $\phi$ is a bijection so $\phi^{-1}(t) =
\{a,b\} = V(x-a,y-b)$ is closed. So $\phi$ is a homeomorphism.

But $A(\A^1) = k[t]$ is integrally closed in $k(t)$ and $A(X)$ is not
integrally closed by (a), so $\phi$ cannot be an isomorphism.

\subprob{c}

We note that $y^2-x^3, y^2-x^2(x-1)$ are irreducible without giving
the explicit proof here. Let $I := (y^2-x^3)$ and $J :=
(y^2-x^2(x-1))$. Assume we have inverse isomorphisms $\phi : V(I) \to
V(J)$ and $\psi : V(J) \to V(I)$. As proved in lecture, $\phi, \psi$
must be restrictions of polynomial maps $\A^2 \to \A^2$. Then we have
induced polynomial maps $\phi^*, \psi^* : k[x,y] \to k[x,y]$ inducing
inverse isomorphisms $k[x,y]/J \simeq k[x,y]/I$ of $k$-algebras. I.e.,
$\phi^*$ must send $J$ bijectively to $I$.\footnote{This solution came
  from discussion with Aaron Landesman and Rahul Dalal.}

Then we must have $\psi^*(y^2-x^3) = c(y^2-x^2(x-1))$ for some $0 \ne
c \in k[x,y]$. Then $\phi^*(c)\phi^*(y^2-x^2(x-1)) = y^2-x^3$, and
since $y^2-x^3$ is irreducible and $\phi^*(y^2-x^2(x-1)) \in I$, it
follows that $c \in k$. Now $\psi^*$ is polynomial, so it follows that
we must have $\phi^*(x) = a_1x + a_2$ and $\phi^*(y) =$

\subprob{d}

We claim that it is necessary and sufficient that:
\begin{enumerate}
\item there is root $\zeta \in k$ of $t^2 + 1 \in k[t]$;
\item $\ch(k) \ne 2$.
\end{enumerate}
By the argument from 2c, there is an isomorphism $V(x^2+y^2-1) \to
V(xy-1)$ and only if there is a polynomial map $\phi : k[x,y] \to
k[x,y]$ sending $x^2+y^2-1 \mapsto xy-1$.

